.TH "vringh_init_user" 9 "vringh_init_user" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
vringh_init_user \- initialize a vringh for a userspace vring.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" vringh_init_user
.BI "(struct vringh *vrh "  ","
.BI "u64 features "  ","
.BI "unsigned int num "  ","
.BI "bool weak_barriers "  ","
.BI "vring_desc_t __user *desc "  ","
.BI "vring_avail_t __user *avail "  ","
.BI "vring_used_t __user *used "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "vrh" 12
the vringh to initialize.
.IP "features" 12
the feature bits for this ring.
.IP "num" 12
the number of elements.
.IP "weak_barriers" 12
true if we only need memory barriers, not I/O.
.IP "desc" 12
the userpace descriptor pointer.
.IP "avail" 12
the userpace avail pointer.
.IP "used" 12
the userpace used pointer.
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Returns an error if num is invalid: you should check pointers
yourself!
